  {
    "id": "1747900000008",
    "channel_id": "19:chan-gocrft-dsn03@thread.tacv2",
    "team_id": "19:team-gocrft01@thread.tacv2",
    "from_user_id": "user-jmurray",
    "from_display_name": "Jason Murray",
    "content": "Design question: for a config loader, functional options vs a Config struct you pass in? Leaning options for the optional fields.",
    "content_type": "html",
    "importance": "normal",
    "created_date": "2025-10-04T08:24:14Z"
  },
  {
    "id": "1747900000009",
    "channel_id": "19:chan-gocrft-dsn03@thread.tacv2",
    "team_id": "19:team-gocrft01@thread.tacv2",
    "from_user_id": "user-daniel",
    "from_display_name": "Daniel Okafor",
    "content": "Options age better for libraries since you can add fields without breaking callers. Struct is fine for internal stuff.",
    "content_type": "html",
    "importance": "normal",
    "created_date": "2025-10-04T08:33:13Z"
  },
  {
    "id": "1747900000010",
    "channel_id": "19:chan-gocrft-dsn03@thread.tacv2",
    "team_id": "19:team-gocrft01@thread.tacv2",
    "from_user_id": "user-tomas",
    "from_display_name": "Tomás Alvarez",
    "content": "Agree on options. Just keep a sane zero-value default so New() with no opts still works. People love that.",
    "content_type": "html",
    "importance": "normal",
    "created_date": "2025-10-04T08:47:11Z"
  },
  {
    "id": "1747900000011",
    "channel_id": "19:chan-gocrft-dsn03@thread.tacv2",
    "team_id": "19:team-gocrft01@thread.tacv2",
    "from_user_id": "user-jmurray",
    "from_display_name": "Jason Murray",
    "content": "Perfect, functional options with a usable zero value it is. Thanks both.",
    "content_type": "html",
    "importance": "normal",
    "created_date": "2025-10-04T08:52:40Z"
  },
  {
    "id": "1747900000012",
    "channel_id": "19:chan-gocrft-help04@thread.tacv2",
    "team_id": "19:team-gocrft01@thread.tacv2",
    "from_user_id": "user-nina",
    "from_display_name": "Nina Kowalski",
    "content": "Newish to Go. Why does my goroutine not finish before main exits? Do I always need a WaitGroup?",
    "content_type": "html",
    "importance": "normal",
    "created_date": "2025-10-27T06:10:07Z"
  },
  {
    "id": "1747900000013",
    "channel_id": "19:chan-gocrft-help04@thread.tacv2",
    "team_id": "19:team-gocrft01@thread.tacv2",
    "from_user_id": "user-jmurray",
    "from_display_name": "Jason Murray",
    "content": "Yep, main doesn't wait for goroutines. A WaitGroup or a done channel is the usual fix. Add wg.Add(1) before, wg.Done() inside, wg.Wait() at the end.",
    "content_type": "html",
    "importance": "normal",
    "created_date": "2025-10-27T06:18:06Z"
  },
  {
    "id": "1747900000014",
    "channel_id": "19:chan-gocrft-help04@thread.tacv2",
    "team_id": "19:team-gocrft01@thread.tacv2",
    "from_user_id": "user-nina",
    "from_display_name": "Nina Kowalski",
    "content": "That did it, thank you! The Add-before-the-goroutine bit was what I was missing.",
    "content_type": "html",
    "importance": "normal",
    "created_date": "2025-10-27T06:25:35Z"
  },
  {
